# Angular: Component Tests Required

Every Angular component must have a corresponding **`.spec.ts`** test file in the same directory as the component.

## Rule

- For each **`*.component.ts`** file, there must be a **`*.component.spec.ts`** file next to it.
- The spec file must contain at least one test (e.g. "should create") and should cover the component’s main behaviour.
- When **creating a new component**, create the spec file at the same time; do not leave components without tests.

## File layout

```
core/components/app-nav/
  app-nav.component.ts
  app-nav.component.html
  app-nav.component.spec.ts   ← required
```

## Checklist

- [ ] New component created → create `*.component.spec.ts` in the same folder.
- [ ] Spec imports the component and uses `TestBed` to compile and create it.
- [ ] At least one test (e.g. `it('should create', () => { ... })`) and tests for important behaviour (e.g. user actions, inputs, outputs).

## Example

```typescript
// app-nav.component.spec.ts
import { ComponentFixture, TestBed } from '@angular/core/testing';
import { AppNavComponent } from './app-nav.component';

describe('AppNavComponent', () => {
  let fixture: ComponentFixture<AppNavComponent>;

  beforeEach(async () => {
    await TestBed.configureTestingModule({
      imports: [AppNavComponent],
      providers: [ /* Router, services, etc. */ ],
    }).compileComponents();
    fixture = TestBed.createComponent(AppNavComponent);
    fixture.detectChanges();
  });

  it('should create', () => {
    expect(fixture.componentInstance).toBeTruthy();
  });
});
```

Apply this to all components. If you add a new component, add its spec file in the same step.
